        args='{"prompt":"What does the S-1 filing {{spacex_s1}} disclose about the AI segment (xAI), including revenue, Segment Adjusted EBITDA, GPU cluster capacity, Grok product, training compute, customer concentration, and any forward-looking statements about commercialization or monetization?"}',
        parsed_args={
            'prompt': 'What does the S-1 filing {{spacex_s1}} disclose about the AI segment (xAI), including revenue, Segment Adjusted EBITDA, GPU cluster capacity, Grok product, training compute, customer concentration, and any forward-looking statements about commercialization or monetization?'
        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# AI Segment (xAI) Disclosures in the S-1 Filing\n\n## 1. Revenue\n\n| Period | Revenue |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 (three months ended March 31, 2026) | **$818 million** |\n| Full year 2025 | **$3,201 million** |\n| Q1 2025 (three months ended March 31, 2025) | Implied ~$727 million (based on the disclosed $91 million YoY increase) |\n\nRevenue increased **$91 million** year-over-year in Q1 2026, driven by **higher X and Grok subscriptions**.\n\n### Revenue Recognition\nThe filing breaks AI revenue into three streams:\n- **Subscription revenue** — recognized ratably over the subscription term (month-to-month up to one year)\n- **Data licensing revenue** — recognized ratably over the period (month-to-month up to two years) as the customer consumes and benefits from the licensed data\n- **API access to Grok models** — recognized ratably over the contract term (typically month-to-month or up to one year) for stand-ready access, or as services are consumed for usage-based arrangements\n\n---\n\n## 2. Segment Adjusted EBITDA and Loss from Operations\n\n| Period | Loss from Operations | Segment Adjusted EBITDA |\n|---|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | **$(2,469) million** | **$(609) million** |\n| Q1 2025 | $(936) million | $(112) million |\n| Full year 2025 | **$(6,355) million** | **$(1,237) million** |\n| Full year 2024 | $(1,561) million | $347 million |\n| Full year 2023 | $(3,973) million | $1,222 million |\n\nThe filing attributes the widening losses to the segment\'s **"earlier stage of development and continued investments to support long-term growth opportunities in AI."** Notably, the segment was EBITDA-positive in 2023 and 2024 before turning negative in 2025 and Q1 2026, coinciding with the massive ramp in compute infrastructure spending.\n\nSegment Adjusted EBITDA is disclosed as a **non-GAAP measure**, with a cross-reference to the MD&A section for reconciliations to segment income (loss) from operations (the most directly comparable GAAP measure).\n\n---\n\n## 3. GPU Cluster Capacity and Compute Infrastructure\n\n### Nameplate Compute Draw\n\n| Period | Nameplate Compute Draw (gigawatts) |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | **1.0 GW** |\n| Q1 2025 | 0.3 GW |\n| Full year 2025 | 0.8 GW |\n| Full year 2024 | 0.3 GW |\n| Full year 2023 | 0 GW |\n\n### COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II Data Centers\n- **COLOSSUS** (Memphis, Tennessee): First cluster brought online in **122 days**, repurposing the shell of an existing factory\n- **COLOSSUS II**: First cluster brought online even faster — **91 days**\n- Industry benchmark for comparison: ~**2 years** for a 100 MW greenfield data center\n- Together, COLOSSUS and COLOSSUS II collectively provide approximately **1.0 gigawatt of compute power**, with additional power capacity available for data center operations\n- COLOSSUS II achieved **construction costs considerably lower than industry benchmarks on a per-megawatt basis**\n- COLOSSUS II is capable of operating entirely on **self-built behind-the-meter gigawatt-scale natural gas power generation**\n\n### Market Opportunity Sizing\nThe filing quantifies the AI compute infrastructure market:\n- AI workload demand corresponds to **104 million GPUs required**\n- Applied assumptions: **80% utilization rate** (per National Electrical Installation Standards) and a **GPU rental rate of $3.33/hour** (per Silicon Data, based on the median of neocloud GPU rental rates in 2025)\n- The filing notes the rental rate has historically varied subject to market conditions\n\n### Capital Expenditures\n\n| Period | AI Segment CapEx |\n|---|---|\n| Q1 2026 | **$7,723 million** |\n| 2025 | Not fully stated in the provided chunks (Space was $3,832M; Connectivity was $4,178M; AI figure was cut off) |\n\nThe AI segment\'s Q1 2026 CapEx of $7.7 billion dramatically exceeds the Space ($1,052M) and Connectivity ($1,332M) segments, underscoring the capital-intensive nature of the buildout.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Grok Product Family\n\n### Model Development Timeline\n- **Grok-1**: Launched November 2023\n- **Four major versions** released since launch, culminating in **Grok-4.3 (April 2026)**\n- **Grok 5** currently in development, expected to further expand reasoning fidelity, multimodal integration, and domain-specific performance\n- Described as achieving **"one of the fastest iteration cycles in the industry"**\n\n### Performance Benchmarks\n- Within **two years** of its initial model release, Grok achieved **frontier-level performance in scientific reasoning**, as measured by its **GPQA Diamond score** (an industry benchmark evaluating AI models on standardized questions written and validated by experts)\n- Achieved this milestone **on a faster timeline than reported by other leading model providers**\n\n### Parameter Scaling\n- Ongoing training of next-generation models is expected to scale toward **multiple trillions of parameters**\n- The filing states this "could represent a step change in reasoning depth and overall intelligence"\n- Larger parameter counts are described as enabling the model to capture more complex relationships, store greater amounts of knowledge, and achieve higher reasoning capability\n\n### Product Offerings Defined\nThe filing formally defines several Grok-related products:\n- **Grok**: The family of frontier models, described as "a core pillar of our mission to advance humanity\'s understanding of the universe through the development of truth-seeking artificial intelligence"\n- **Grok API**: Application programming interface enabling developers to access and integrate Grok models into external software applications and workflows\n- **Grok Business**: Subscription-based offering providing organizations with access to Grok models and related tools for internal business applications\n- **Grok Enterprise**: Subscription-based offering for organizations, designed for enterprise deployment\n- **Grok Voice**: The Grok real-time speech engine\n- **Imagine**: The company\'s image and video generation system\n\n### Truth-Seeking Mission\nGrok is described as a **"truth-seeking AI model"** built on Elon Musk\'s mission to enable humanity to understand the universe. The filing defines truth-seeking as:\n> "the active, relentless pursuit of what is objectively true about reality, and grounded in evidence, logic, empirical data, and first principles thinking."\n\n### X Platform Integration\n- Grok benefits from integration with **X** (the real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform), which serves as a **"foundational distribution and data engine"** for the AI ecosystem\n- Real-time data integration through X enables **dynamic awareness of current events and user discourse** (subject to some limitations for certain content)\n- Grok enhances the X ecosystem by improving content understanding, personalization, and recommendation systems, thereby increasing user engagement and platform intelligence\n- Plans to **further embed Grok throughout the X platform** to enhance discovery, analysis of posts, user support, and personalization\n\n---\n\n## 5. Training Compute and R&D Expenses\n\n### R&D Expense Drivers\n- AI segment R&D expenses **mainly relate to the training of Grok**, development/build/testing of next-generation AI-enabled products, and data center costs to train AI-enabled products\n- Costs include **cloud computing expenses**, employee compensation (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation), and **depreciation of GPU hardware**\n- Q1 2026 R&D expense increased by **$1,471 million** YoY, driven by **depreciation of GPU hardware** and cloud computing/data center infrastructure expenses from AI data center expansions\n\n### Cost of Revenue Components\nAI segment cost of revenue includes:\n- **Infrastructure costs** (data center facilities, lease/hosting, support, maintenance, energy, bandwidth, depreciation of servers and networking equipment, public cloud hosting, employee compensation)\n- Revenue share expenses\n- Payment processor fees\n- Payments to creators\n- Amortization of acquired intangible assets\n- Allocated labor and overhead costs\n\n### Vertical Integration as Strategic Differentiator\nThe filing emphasizes that the accelerated rate of innovation "stems from our highly vertically integrated stack: full ownership of training infrastructure, access to" manufacturing, data center infrastructure, and power generation. It states:\n> "Without large-scale, power-efficient infrastructure, AGI cannot be deployed broadly or economically—making such infrastructure a critical strategic differentiator."\n\n---\n\n## 6. Customer Concentration\n\nThe provided chunks do **not** disclose specific customer concentration metrics (e.g., percentage of revenue from top customers) for the AI segment. The filing references three broad customer categories:\n- **Consumer** subscribers (X and Grok subscriptions)\n- **Enterprise** customers (Grok Business, Grok Enterprise, API access)\n- **Government** customers\n\nThe filing mentions a strategic objective of **"Growing Enterprise and Government Adoption of Our AI Offerings"** but does not quantify current concentration in the disclosed portions.\n\n---\n\n## 7. Forward-Looking Statements on Commercialization and Monetization\n\n### Growth and Investment Priority\n> "In our newly acquired AI segment, we plan to prioritize growth and investment to capture significant opportunities in AI applications and compute infrastructure."\n\n### Cost of Revenue Trajectory\n> "We expect AI cost of revenue to increase in absolute dollars as we grow our revenue, and to decrease as a percentage of revenue as we monetize our products and as we expand our service offerings for AI solutions."\n\n### Consumer AI Subscriptions\n- The filing identifies consumer AI subscriptions as a significant market opportunity, driven by demand for AI tools that enhance productivity, creativity, personalization, and real-time assistance\n- Grok\'s integration with X and proprietary access to real-time data inflows is expected to **"better address a broader set of high-frequency, high-value consumer use cases and increase user engagement and willingness to pay, positioning Grok to capture a larger share of the consumer AI"** market\n- Multi-trillion parameter models in the roadmap "could represent a step change in reasoning depth and overall intelligence"\n\n### X as "Everything App"\n- Plans to evolve X into an **"Everything App"** integrating real-time information, communications, media, payments, banking, commerce, and more\n- **X Money** (launched beta November 2025): payments and financial services\n- **X Chat** (released November 2025): end-to-end encrypted messaging with no connection to advertising\n- Further Grok embedding throughout the platform to **"reduce friction for users to adopt paid features"**\n\n### Enterprise and Government Adoption\nThe filing explicitly flags **"Growing Enterprise and Government Adoption of Our AI Offerings"** as a future growth driver, though specific targets are not quantified in the disclosed portions.\n\n### AGI Convergence\n> "We believe AI is rapidly converging toward AGI, where human cognitive capabilities can be replicated and scaled at machine speeds, profoundly augmenting human productivity. Once an AGI system exists, its true value derives from the ability to create limitless duplicates of human-like intelligence, necessitating vast computational resources and cost-efficient deployment to achieve meaningful scale."\n\n### Orbital and Lunar AI Compute\n- The company expects to **leverage rockets and satellites for massive orbital deployments of AI infrastructure**, helping develop and monetize Grok faster than competitors dependent on finite Earth-based power\n- If a **lunar presence** is achieved, it will potentially enable **terawatt-scale annual AI compute growth**, support deeper space exploration and industrialization, and serve as a stepping stone to Mars civilization\n- The next trillion-dollar market is identified as **AI compute**\n\n### Acquisition Context\n- **xAI was founded in 2023 and acquired by SpaceX in early 2026**, making it an integral pillar of the vertically integrated company\n- The AI segment is described as **"newly acquired"** throughout the filing\n\n---\n\n## Summary Table\n\n| Metric | Q1 2026 | FY 2025 | FY 2024 | FY 2023 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Revenue | $818M | $3,201M | — | — |\n| Loss from Operations | $(2,469)M | $(6,355)M | $(1,561)M | $(3,973)M |\n| Segment Adjusted EBITDA | $(609)M | $(1,237)M | $347M | $1,222M |\n| Nameplate Compute Draw | 1.0 GW | 0.8 GW | 0.3 GW | 0 GW |\n| Capital Expenditures | $7,723M | — | — | — |',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=52.968,
