    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided S-1 filing excerpts, here is a detailed breakdown of what the document discloses regarding the Space segment, Starship development, government contracts, launch metrics, and forward-looking market opportunities:\n\n### 1. Launch Services Revenue & Financial Performance\n*   **Recent Financials:** For the three months ended March 31, 2026, the Space segment generated revenue of $619 million, a loss from operations of $(662) million, and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $(351) million. For the full year 2025, the segment generated revenue of $4,086 million, a loss from operations of $(657) million, and Segment Adjusted EBITDA of $653 million.\n*   **Revenue Breakdown:** Space revenue is split between **Launch Services** (point-in-time recognition for deploying payloads using Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy) and **Launch & Development** (over-time recognition for developing spacecraft and providing mission services for government programs using Falcon 9, Falcon Heavy, Starship, and Dragon). \n*   **Revenue Mix Trends:** In Q1 2026, Launch Services accounted for 53.3% of Space revenue, while Launch & Development accounted for 46.7%. The company expects Launch & Development to represent a larger portion of Space revenue in the future as it serves more long-term government contracts.\n*   **Inter-segment Allocation:** The Space segment only recognizes revenue from customer launches. For internal Starlink satellite launches, no inter-segment revenue is recognized; instead, those launch costs are capitalized within the Connectivity segment. The company also expects to allocate a significant amount of future launch capacity to its AI segment. \n*   **EBITDA Declines:** Space Segment Adjusted EBITDA decreased by $501 million in 2025 (down to $653 million from $1,154 million in 2024). This decline was primarily driven by accelerated investments in the Starship vehicle and launch facilities, partially offset by increased revenue from NASA Cargo Resupply Services (CRS) and a U.S. Department of War contract.\n\n### 2. Starship Development & Commercialization\n*   **R&D Investments:** The Space segment funded $930 million in R&D for Starship in Q1 2026, and $3,004 million for the full year 2025. R&D expenses are expected to increase in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue in 2026.\n*   **Vehicle Capabilities:** Starship is described as the world’s first fully, rapidly reusable launch vehicle. The next-generation Starship V3 is designed to carry 100 metric tons to Earth’s orbit in a reusable configuration, with future generations (potentially as soon as V4) designed to reach 200 metric tons.\n*   **Testing Milestones:** To date, SpaceX has executed 11 Starship flight tests. A 12th flight test is scheduled, which will debut the next-generation Starship vehicle and Super Heavy booster, powered by the next evolution of the Raptor engine, launching from a newly designed pad at Starbase. Innovative milestones include booster catches using “chopstick” arms.\n*   **Commercialization Timeline & Cost Capitalization:** Starship is expected to commence payload delivery to orbit in the second half of 2026. Once commercialized (delivering payload to orbit), Starship costs will generally be capitalized and depreciated in the cost of revenue of the segment associated with the payload, rather than being expensed as R&D. \n\n### 3. Government Contracts (NSSL, NASA, DoD)\n*   **Primary U.S. Government Provider:** SpaceX is the primary launch provider for the U.S. government. In 2025, it launched 11 of 12 National Security Space Launch (“NSSL”) medium and heavy lift missions and all five U.S. crew and cargo missions to the International Space Station for NASA.\n*   **NSSL Phase 3:** U.S. national security customers have awarded approximately $13.7 billion across the NSSL Program’s Phase 3 Lane 2 contracts through 2032, supporting approximately 54 missions from 2025 to 2032. The overall Phase 3 manifest nearly doubles Phase 2’s manifest to 84 missions.\n*   **Government Spending:** According to the Space Foundation, excluding classified spending, U.S. Government space spending in 2024 totaled approximately $77 billion.\n\n### 4. Falcon 9 Launch Cadence & Mission Count\n*   **Historical Scale:** As of March 31, 2026, SpaceX had completed approximately 650 orbital space launches, with over 540 completed by flight-proven Falcon rockets. Falcon 9 has approximately 620 orbital launches and an over 99% mission success rate.\n*   **2025 Metrics:** In 2025 alone, SpaceX completed 170 missions across Falcon and Starship vehicles, including 165 Falcon 9 launches (157 flight-proven) and 159 flight-proven booster launches. The company launched over 2,200 metric tons, representing over 80% of mass to orbit for the world in 2025.\n*   **Q1 2026 vs. Q1 2025:** Falcon launches totaled 40 in Q1 2026 (39 flight-proven) compared to 36 in Q1 2025. Customer launches decreased from 12 to 7, while internal launches increased from 24 to 33.\n*   **Annual Cadence:** Falcon launches for 2023, 2024, and 2025 totaled 96, 134, and 165, respectively. Customer launches for those years were 33, 45, and 43, while internal launches were 63, 89, and 122.\n*   **Future Cadence:** While Falcon 9 currently drives the majority of launch activity (averaging 13 metric tons per mission), the company expects Falcon 9 launches to decrease over time as Starship becomes a larger contributor to launch volume.\n\n### 5. Forward-Looking Market Opportunities & Mars Vision\n*   **Space Economy Growth:** Driven by reduced launch costs, active maneuverable satellites in orbit have grown from less than 1,000 in 2015 to approximately 12,700 as of March 31, 2026 (SpaceX operates ~75% of them). Payload launched to orbit grew from ~220 metric tons in 2012 to ~2,600 metric tons in 2025.\n*   **Internal Growth Absorption:** Space revenue growth is expected to be lower than total company revenue growth because internal businesses (Connectivity and AI) will continue to absorb most of the growth in launch capacity.\n*   **Starship-Enabled Markets:** Over the long term, SpaceX expects Starship to unlock entirely new categories of missions, including:\n    *   **Point-to-point terrestrial travel:** Ultra-fast long-haul Earth transport for passengers and cargo.\n    *   **Space tourism:** Increasing interest in human space travel.\n    *   **In-orbit manufacturing:** Leveraging microgravity to produce materials, pharmaceuticals, and advanced components.\n    *   **Multiplanetary Transport:** Large-scale passenger and cargo missions to the Moon and Mars to establish permanent human settlements.\n    *   **Lunar/Martian Infrastructure:** Energy production (large-scale solar) and manufacturing capabilities on the Moon and Mars to support a self-sustaining multiplanetary civilization.\n*   **Dependency Risks:** The S-1 cautions that if Starship development is delayed, it will impede the deployment of next-generation V3 satellites, V2 Mobile satellites, and orbital AI compute infrastructure, as current Falcon rockets are not capable of deploying these next-gen assets.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
    duration_seconds=48.237,
    error=None,
    success=True
)
