        output='Based on the provided S-1 filing excerpts, here is what SpaceX discloses about its Connectivity segment (Starlink), broken down by the key areas you requested:\n\n### 1. Subscriber Growth\n*   **Massive Scale and Rapid Growth:** As of March 31, 2026, Starlink had approximately 10.3 million subscribers, up 105% from 5.0 million a year prior. For the full year 2025, subscribers grew to 8.9 million (up 99.9% from 4.4 million in 2024, which itself was up from 2.3 million in 2023).\n*   **Counting Methodology:** "Starlink Subscribers" are counted on a per-Service Line basis at the end of a period. It includes both Personal (Residential, Roam) and Business (Local Priority, Global Priority) plans, but excludes managed enterprise and government contracts. \n*   **Underlying User Base:** Because multiple people can share a single Service Line (e.g., a household), the actual number of individual end-users is "meaningfully higher" than the 10.3 million reported.\n*   **Global Reach:** Subscribers span 164 countries, territories, and markets, representing a small fraction of an estimated 3.3 billion potential end users in those markets.\n\n### 2. ARPU Trends\n*   **Declining ARPU:** Starlink Subscriber ARPU (Average Revenue Per User) has steadily declined: $99 in 2023, $91 in 2024, $81 in 2025, and $66 in Q1 2026 (down 22.9% from $86 in Q1 2025).\n*   **Drivers of Decline:** The drop is primarily attributed to international expansion and the introduction of lower-priced service plans.\n*   **Strategic Priority:** SpaceX explicitly states its strategy prioritizes driving sustainable revenue growth, expanding margins through operational efficiencies, and expanding global connectivity/market access—rather than prioritizing ARPU increases. The company expects ARPU to continue declining over the next few years as its subscriber base outside North America grows.\n\n### 3. Direct-to-Cell Mobile Service (Starlink Mobile)\n*   **Current Capabilities:** The "V1" Mobile constellation consists of approximately 650 satellites in orbit. It currently enables light data, text messaging (SMS), and over-the-top voice services (e.g., WhatsApp, FaceTime). As of March 31, 2026, this serves approximately 7.4 million monthly unique devices across ~30 countries.\n*   **Future Capabilities:** SpaceX is developing comprehensive satellite-to-mobile services, including broadband data and IoT connectivity, which are expected to deliver resilient, infrastructure-independent connectivity worldwide and enable 5G.\n*   **Partnerships & Revenue Model:** The company has partnerships with ~30 Mobile Network Operators (MNOs) on six continents, covering an area home to 1.9 billion people. SpaceX charges MNOs either a fixed fee or a per-mobile user fee, which is typically passed through to the end customer by the carrier.\n\n### 4. Enterprise & Government Revenue\n*   **Enterprise Solutions:** Starlink serves a wide array of industries (construction, aviation, maritime, retail, etc.) through a direct, vertical-specific sales model. Revenue is generated via contracts structured as subscriptions, data consumption, capacity, or percentage-of-completion.\n*   **Government Solutions:** Revenue is generated via long-term contracts for "Starshield," a secure satellite network designed specifically for government entities.\n*   **Financial Performance:** \n    *   In Q1 2026, enterprise and government revenue increased by $126 million year-over-year. This was driven by $209 million in growth from aviation, maritime, and other enterprise business, and $85 million in mobile connectivity, which partially offset a $175 million decrease in government connectivity.\n    *   For the full year 2025, enterprise and government connectivity revenue increased by $1,411 million, driven by $1,218 million in enterprise growth (including $632 million in mobile connectivity) and $193 million in government growth.\n\n### 5. Satellite Manufacturing & Network Scale\n*   **Current Constellation:** As of March 31, 2026, SpaceX operates approximately 9,600 Starlink broadband and mobile satellites in Low-Earth Orbit (LEO), accounting for roughly 75% of all active maneuverable satellites in orbit.\n*   **Next-Generation V3 Satellites:** SpaceX expects to commence deploying V3 satellites in the second half of 2026 using Starship. These satellites are designed to offer 1 Tbps of downlink capacity per satellite.\n*   **Launch Efficiency:** A single Starship launch will be capable of deploying up to 60 V3 satellites to LEO, representing a potential twenty-fold increase in Starlink downlink capacity deployed relative to a Falcon 9 launch.\n*   **Vertical Integration:** The company highlights its "highly verticalized supply chain" and in-house manufacturing as key drivers of scale, efficiency, and the compounding competitive advantage of its LEO constellations.\n\n### 6. Forward-Looking Statements: Market Opportunity, Capacity, and Revenue Growth\n*   **Total Addressable Market (TAM):** SpaceX estimates a $1.6 trillion total market opportunity across Starlink Broadband and Starlink Mobile, driven primarily by consumer use cases. Starlink Broadband alone represents an approximately $870 billion opportunity. The company expects the market to extend well beyond traditional definitions as connectivity becomes embedded in transportation networks, autonomous systems, and smart devices.\n*   **Revenue Growth:** The Connectivity segment generated $11.4 billion in revenue in 2025 (up 49.8% YoY) and $3.26 billion in Q1 2026 (up 31.6% YoY). SpaceX expects to drive meaningful subscriber and revenue growth by expanding its retail distribution network, executing region-specific marketing, and demonstrating superior speed/affordability not just in rural areas, but also in suburban/urban regions with wireline broadband options.\n*   **Capacity and Margin Expansion:** The deployment of V3 satellites via Starship will massively scale downlink capacity. The company expects to expand margins through operational efficiencies and technological advancements, driving strong sequential Connectivity Segment Adjusted EBITDA growth. \n*   **Space Segment Synergy:** The filing notes that while the Space segment\'s revenue growth looks relatively lower because it does not recognize revenue for internal Starlink launches (costs are capitalized and depreciated within the Connectivity segment), this launch capacity provides "foundational strategic value" bolstering the growth of both Connectivity and the newly acquired AI segment.',
