        args='{"final_result":"## Investment Narrative by Segment — SpaceX S-1 (Filed May 20, 2026)\\n\\nAll figures are from the retrospectively recast consolidated financial statements, which include xAI (merged Feb 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI Mar 28, 2025) for all historical periods presented. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 1. SPACE SEGMENT — \\"Launch Monopoly Funding the Starship Option\\"\\n\\n**Disclosed economics (presently validated):**\\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| Segment Revenue | $3,557M | $3,796M | $4,086M | $619M |\\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA | n/d | $1,154M¹ | $653M | $(351)M |\\n| Starship R&D | — | — | $3,004M | $930M |\\n\\n¹ Implied from disclosed YoY decline of $501M.\\n\\n**Disclosed KPIs:**\\n- ~650 orbital launches cumulative; 170 missions in 2025 (165 Falcon 9, 157 flight-proven)\\n- 11 of 12 NSSL medium/heavy missions in 2025; all 5 NASA ISS crew/cargo missions\\n- ~$13.7B awarded across NSSL Phase 3 Lane 2 through 2032 (~54 missions); Phase 3 manifest = 84 missions (nearly 2× Phase 2)\\n- >80% of global mass-to-orbit in 2025; >99% Falcon 9 mission success rate\\n- 11 Starship flight tests completed; 12th scheduled\\n\\n**Equity story:** A profitable, government-anchored launch monopoly (NSSL, NASA CRS, DoD) generating ~$4B revenue and positive EBITDA in 2025, with the option value of Starship commercialization (payload delivery expected H2 2026) and long-dated TAM expansion (point-to-point Earth travel, space tourism, in-orbit manufacturing, multiplanetary transport). The present economics are real and contracted; the upside is forward-looking but anchored to a flight-tested vehicle and a $13.7B contracted backlog.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 2. CONNECTIVITY SEGMENT — \\"The Cash Engine\\"\\n\\n**Disclosed economics (presently validated):**\\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| Segment Revenue | $3,869M | $7,599M | $11,387M | $3,257M |\\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA | $1,602M | $3,849M | $7,168M | $2,087M |\\n| YoY Revenue Growth | — | +96.4% | +49.8% | +31.6% |\\n\\n**Disclosed KPIs:**\\n- Starlink subscribers: 2.3M (2023) → 4.4M (2024) → 8.9M (2025) → 10.3M (Q1 2026); +105% YoY in Q1 2026\\n- ARPU declining by design: $99 (2023) → $91 (2024) → $81 (2025) → $66 (Q1 2026), driven by international expansion and lower-priced plans\\n- ~9,600 Starlink broadband/mobile satellites in LEO (~75% of all active maneuverable satellites)\\n- Direct-to-Cell: ~650 V1 Mobile satellites; 7.4M monthly unique devices across ~30 countries; partnerships with ~30 MNOs covering 1.9B people\\n- Enterprise + government revenue +$1,411M YoY in 2025 (incl. $632M mobile connectivity growth)\\n- Disclosed TAM: ~$1.6T (Starlink Broadband ~$870B + Starlink Mobile)\\n\\n**Equity story:** The most economically validated segment. $11.4B revenue growing ~50% with $7.2B Segment Adjusted EBITDA (63% EBITDA margin) and a clear KPI flywheel (subscribers, satellites, mobile devices, MNO partnerships). ARPU decline is a disclosed strategic choice to drive volume. Forward-looking upside (V3 satellites at 1 Tbps each via Starship, 5G direct-to-cell, margin expansion) is layered on top of already-profitable, scaling economics.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### 3. AI SEGMENT — \\"Compute as the Next Trillion-Dollar Market\\"\\n\\n**Disclosed economics (presently validated):**\\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 | Q1 2026 Annualized |\\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\\n| Segment Revenue | $2,961M | $2,620M | $3,201M | $818M | ~$3,272M |\\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA | $1,222M | $347M | $(1,237)M | $(609)M | ~$(2,436)M |\\n| Loss from Operations | $(3,973)M | $(1,561)M | $(6,355)M | $(2,469)M | ~$(9,876)M |\\n| Nameplate Compute Draw | 0 GW | 0.3 GW | 0.8 GW | 1.0 GW | — |\\n| CapEx | $463M | $5,633M | $12,727M | $7,723M | ~$30,892M |\\n\\n**Disclosed KPIs:**\\n- 1.0 GW nameplate compute draw (COLOSSUS + COLOSSUS II online); COLOSSUS built in 122 days, COLOSSUS II in 91 days (vs. ~2-year industry benchmark for 100 MW greenfield)\\n- Grok model family: Grok-1 (Nov 2023) → Grok-4.3 (Apr 2026); Grok 5 in development\\n- Frontier-level GPQA Diamond score within 2 years of first release\\n- Revenue streams: X/Grok subscriptions, advertising, data licensing, Grok API/Business/Enterprise/Voice, Imagine\\n- Market sizing: 104M GPUs required at 80% utilization and $3.33/hour rental (per Silicon Data)\\n\\n**Equity story:** The narrative is almost entirely forward-looking. Revenue is essentially flat over 2 years (+8.1% cumulative from $2,961M to $3,201M), and the segment flipped from $1.2B positive EBITDA in 2023 to a ~$2.4B annualized EBITDA loss in Q1 2026 — a ~$3.6B swing — while CapEx annualized to ~$30.9B. The disclosed value proposition rests on: (i) AGI convergence (\\"AI is rapidly converging toward AGI\\"), (ii) multi-trillion parameter models representing \\"a step change in reasoning depth,\\" (iii) orbital and lunar AI compute (\\"terawatt-scale annual AI compute growth\\" if a lunar presence is achieved), (iv) X evolving into an \\"Everything App\\" (payments, banking, commerce), and (v) growing enterprise/government adoption (unquantified). Customer concentration is not disclosed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Which Segment\'s Equity Story Relies Most Heavily on Forward Expectations?\\n\\n**The AI segment.**\\n\\nThe contrast across the three segments is stark when measured against presently disclosed economics:\\n\\n| Dimension | Space | Connectivity | AI |\\n|---|---|---|---|\\n| FY2025 Revenue | $4.1B | $11.4B | $3.2B |\\n| FY2025 Segment Adj. EBITDA | $653M | $7,168M | $(1,237)M |\\n| EBITDA Trend | Profitable, declining on Starship R&D | Profitable and expanding | Swung from +$1.2B to negative; worsening |\\n| Revenue Growth (2-yr) | +14.9% | +194% | +8.1% |\\n| CapEx Intensity (FY2025) | $3.8B | $4.2B | $12.7B |\\n| Contracted Backlog / Validated KPIs | $13.7B NSSL Phase 3; 170 missions/yr | 10.3M subs; 9,600 sats; 7.4M mobile devices | 1.0 GW compute; Grok-4.3 (no revenue/customer KPIs tied to compute) |\\n| Forward-Looking Pillars | Starship commercialization (H2 2026); Mars | V3 satellites; 5G D2C; margin expansion | AGI; multi-trillion-param models; orbital/lunar terawatt compute; \\"Everything App\\" |\\n\\n**Why AI relies most on forward expectations:**\\n\\n1. **Deteriorating present economics.** Segment Adjusted EBITDA moved from +$1,222M (2023) → +$347M (2024) → −$1,237M (2025) → −$609M in Q1 2026 alone (≈ −$2.4B annualized). The filing attributes this to the segment\'s \\"earlier stage of development and continued investments to support long-term growth opportunities in AI\\" — explicitly framing current losses as a forward bet.\\n\\n2. **Revenue is not validating the spend.** Despite $12.7B of CapEx in 2025 and ~$30.9B annualized in Q1 2026, revenue grew only ~8% cumulatively over two years and is essentially flat on a Q1-annualized basis. The compute ramp (0 → 1.0 GW) is not yet translating into proportional revenue.\\n\\n3. **The TAM and unit economics are assumption-driven, not realized.** The 104M-GPU / $3.33-per-hour / 80%-utilization market sizing is sourced to third parties (Silicon Data, National Electrical Installation Standards) and described as subject to market conditions — not a disclosed customer book or contracted revenue.\\n\\n4. **The strategic value propositions are aspirational.** AGI convergence, multi-trillion-parameter \\"step change,\\" orbital AI compute, lunar \\"terawatt-scale annual AI compute growth,\\" and X as an \\"Everything App\\" are roadmap/mission statements, not presently disclosed economics. Several depend on Starship success (itself a forward-looking milestone).\\n\\n5. **Customer concentration and monetization metrics are absent.** Unlike Connectivity (subscribers, ARPU, MNO partners) and Space (NSSL backlog, mission count), the AI segment discloses no customer count, no API revenue, no enterprise/government adoption metrics, and no unit economics for Grok subscriptions.\\n\\nBy contrast, **Connectivity** is the most economically validated (profitable, scaling, KPI-rich), and **Space** sits in the middle — profitable today with a large contracted government backlog, but with its largest upside (Starship, Mars) still forward-looking. The **AI segment** is the only one where the equity story is predominantly a forward-expectations narrative layered on presently negative and worsening economics.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Sources\\n\\n{\\n  \\"sources\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\"url\\": \\"https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm\\",\\n      \\"name\\": \\"Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) Form S-1, filed May 20, 2026 — Segment financials, KPIs, MD&A, and forward-looking disclosures for Space, Connectivity, and AI segments\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}"}',
        parsed_args={
            'final_result': '## Investment Narrative by Segment — SpaceX S-1 (Filed May 20, 2026)\n\nAll figures are from the retrospectively recast consolidated financial statements, which include xAI (merged Feb 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI Mar 28, 2025) for all historical periods presented. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations.\n\n---\n\n### 1. SPACE SEGMENT — "Launch Monopoly Funding the Starship Option"\n\n**Disclosed economics (presently validated):**\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Segment Revenue | $3,557M | $3,796M | $4,086M | $619M |\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA | n/d | $1,154M¹ | $653M | $(351)M |\n| Starship R&D | — | — | $3,004M | $930M |\n\n¹ Implied from disclosed YoY decline of $501M.\n\n**Disclosed KPIs:**\n- ~650 orbital launches cumulative; 170 missions in 2025 (165 Falcon 9, 157 flight-proven)\n- 11 of 12 NSSL medium/heavy missions in 2025; all 5 NASA ISS crew/cargo missions\n- ~$13.7B awarded across NSSL Phase 3 Lane 2 through 2032 (~54 missions); Phase 3 manifest = 84 missions (nearly 2× Phase 2)\n- >80% of global mass-to-orbit in 2025; >99% Falcon 9 mission success rate\n- 11 Starship flight tests completed; 12th scheduled\n\n**Equity story:** A profitable, government-anchored launch monopoly (NSSL, NASA CRS, DoD) generating ~$4B revenue and positive EBITDA in 2025, with the option value of Starship commercialization (payload delivery expected H2 2026) and long-dated TAM expansion (point-to-point Earth travel, space tourism, in-orbit manufacturing, multiplanetary transport). The present economics are real and contracted; the upside is forward-looking but anchored to a flight-tested vehicle and a $13.7B contracted backlog.\n\n---\n\n### 2. CONNECTIVITY SEGMENT — "The Cash Engine"\n\n**Disclosed economics (presently validated):**\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Segment Revenue | $3,869M | $7,599M | $11,387M | $3,257M |\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA | $1,602M | $3,849M | $7,168M | $2,087M |\n| YoY Revenue Growth | — | +96.4% | +49.8% | +31.6% |\n\n**Disclosed KPIs:**\n- Starlink subscribers: 2.3M (2023) → 4.4M (2024) → 8.9M (2025) → 10.3M (Q1 2026); +105% YoY in Q1 2026\n- ARPU declining by design: $99 (2023) → $91 (2024) → $81 (2025) → $66 (Q1 2026), driven by international expansion and lower-priced plans\n- ~9,600 Starlink broadband/mobile satellites in LEO (~75% of all active maneuverable satellites)\n- Direct-to-Cell: ~650 V1 Mobile satellites; 7.4M monthly unique devices across ~30 countries; partnerships with ~30 MNOs covering 1.9B people\n- Enterprise + government revenue +$1,411M YoY in 2025 (incl. $632M mobile connectivity growth)\n- Disclosed TAM: ~$1.6T (Starlink Broadband ~$870B + Starlink Mobile)\n\n**Equity story:** The most economically validated segment. $11.4B revenue growing ~50% with $7.2B Segment Adjusted EBITDA (63% EBITDA margin) and a clear KPI flywheel (subscribers, satellites, mobile devices, MNO partnerships). ARPU decline is a disclosed strategic choice to drive volume. Forward-looking upside (V3 satellites at 1 Tbps each via Starship, 5G direct-to-cell, margin expansion) is layered on top of already-profitable, scaling economics.\n\n---\n\n### 3. AI SEGMENT — "Compute as the Next Trillion-Dollar Market"\n\n**Disclosed economics (presently validated):**\n| Metric | FY2023 | FY2024 | FY2025 | Q1 2026 | Q1 2026 Annualized |\n|---|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Segment Revenue | $2,961M | $2,620M | $3,201M | $818M | ~$3,272M |\n| Segment Adj. EBITDA | $1,222M | $347M | $(1,237)M | $(609)M | ~$(2,436)M |\n| Loss from Operations | $(3,973)M | $(1,561)M | $(6,355)M | $(2,469)M | ~$(9,876)M |\n| Nameplate Compute Draw | 0 GW | 0.3 GW | 0.8 GW | 1.0 GW | — |\n| CapEx | $463M | $5,633M | $12,727M | $7,723M | ~$30,892M |\n\n**Disclosed KPIs:**\n- 1.0 GW nameplate compute draw (COLOSSUS + COLOSSUS II online); COLOSSUS built in 122 days, COLOSSUS II in 91 days (vs. ~2-year industry benchmark for 100 MW greenfield)\n- Grok model family: Grok-1 (Nov 2023) → Grok-4.3 (Apr 2026); Grok 5 in development\n- Frontier-level GPQA Diamond score within 2 years of first release\n- Revenue streams: X/Grok subscriptions, advertising, data licensing, Grok API/Business/Enterprise/Voice, Imagine\n- Market sizing: 104M GPUs required at 80% utilization and $3.33/hour rental (per Silicon Data)\n\n**Equity story:** The narrative is almost entirely forward-looking. Revenue is essentially flat over 2 years (+8.1% cumulative from $2,961M to $3,201M), and the segment flipped from $1.2B positive EBITDA in 2023 to a ~$2.4B annualized EBITDA loss in Q1 2026 — a ~$3.6B swing — while CapEx annualized to ~$30.9B. The disclosed value proposition rests on: (i) AGI convergence ("AI is rapidly converging toward AGI"), (ii) multi-trillion parameter models representing "a step change in reasoning depth," (iii) orbital and lunar AI compute ("terawatt-scale annual AI compute growth" if a lunar presence is achieved), (iv) X evolving into an "Everything App" (payments, banking, commerce), and (v) growing enterprise/government adoption (unquantified). Customer concentration is not disclosed.\n\n---\n\n## Which Segment\'s Equity Story Relies Most Heavily on Forward Expectations?\n\n**The AI segment.**\n\nThe contrast across the three segments is stark when measured against presently disclosed economics:\n\n| Dimension | Space | Connectivity | AI |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| FY2025 Revenue | $4.1B | $11.4B | $3.2B |\n| FY2025 Segment Adj. EBITDA | $653M | $7,168M | $(1,237)M |\n| EBITDA Trend | Profitable, declining on Starship R&D | Profitable and expanding | Swung from +$1.2B to negative; worsening |\n| Revenue Growth (2-yr) | +14.9% | +194% | +8.1% |\n| CapEx Intensity (FY2025) | $3.8B | $4.2B | $12.7B |\n| Contracted Backlog / Validated KPIs | $13.7B NSSL Phase 3; 170 missions/yr | 10.3M subs; 9,600 sats; 7.4M mobile devices | 1.0 GW compute; Grok-4.3 (no revenue/customer KPIs tied to compute) |\n| Forward-Looking Pillars | Starship commercialization (H2 2026); Mars | V3 satellites; 5G D2C; margin expansion | AGI; multi-trillion-param models; orbital/lunar terawatt compute; "Everything App" |\n\n**Why AI relies most on forward expectations:**\n\n1. **Deteriorating present economics.** Segment Adjusted EBITDA moved from +$1,222M (2023) → +$347M (2024) → −$1,237M (2025) → −$609M in Q1 2026 alone (≈ −$2.4B annualized). The filing attributes this to the segment\'s "earlier stage of development and continued investments to support long-term growth opportunities in AI" — explicitly framing current losses as a forward bet.\n\n2. **Revenue is not validating the spend.** Despite $12.7B of CapEx in 2025 and ~$30.9B annualized in Q1 2026, revenue grew only ~8% cumulatively over two years and is essentially flat on a Q1-annualized basis. The compute ramp (0 → 1.0 GW) is not yet translating into proportional revenue.\n\n3. **The TAM and unit economics are assumption-driven, not realized.** The 104M-GPU / $3.33-per-hour / 80%-utilization market sizing is sourced to third parties (Silicon Data, National Electrical Installation Standards) and described as subject to market conditions — not a disclosed customer book or contracted revenue.\n\n4. **The strategic value propositions are aspirational.** AGI convergence, multi-trillion-parameter "step change," orbital AI compute, lunar "terawatt-scale annual AI compute growth," and X as an "Everything App" are roadmap/mission statements, not presently disclosed economics. Several depend on Starship success (itself a forward-looking milestone).\n\n5. **Customer concentration and monetization metrics are absent.** Unlike Connectivity (subscribers, ARPU, MNO partners) and Space (NSSL backlog, mission count), the AI segment discloses no customer count, no API revenue, no enterprise/government adoption metrics, and no unit economics for Grok subscriptions.\n\nBy contrast, **Connectivity** is the most economically validated (profitable, scaling, KPI-rich), and **Space** sits in the middle — profitable today with a large contracted government backlog, but with its largest upside (Starship, Mars) still forward-looking. The **AI segment** is the only one where the equity story is predominantly a forward-expectations narrative layered on presently negative and worsening economics.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) Form S-1, filed May 20, 2026 — Segment financials, KPIs, MD&A, and forward-looking disclosures for Space, Connectivity, and AI segments"\n    }\n  ]\n}'
